article.headline: Iowa State 87, Southeast Missouri State 71
article.story: AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Mike Taylor scored 18 points, freshman Wesley Johnson added 17 points and 12 rebounds and Iowa State buried a season-high 13 3-pointers to beat Southeast Missouri State 87-71 Saturday. Freshman Cory Johnson added a career-high 13 points for the Cyclones (8-5), who shot 52 percent from 3-point range and won for just the second time in seven games. Southeast Missouri State (3-10) cut a 26-point lead down to 79-66 by using the press to break Iowa State's rhythm. But the constant pressure came with a price, as Iowa State found itself in the double-bonus midway through the second half. Although the Cyclones missed 10 of their first 22 free throws, their 3-pointers were too much for the Redhawks to overcome. Taylor's 3 as the shot clock expired put Iowa State ahead 84-67 with 1:53 left. JaJuan Maxwell scored 14 to lead Southeast Missouri State, which lost its fifth straight. Brandon Foust added 13. Iowa State blew things open by nailing 11 of their first 19 attempts from beyond the arc. The Cyclones hit six 3-pointers during an 18-0 run that put them ahead 26-11. They pushed their lead to 24 with a 12-2 spurt, capped when the 6-foot Taylor dribbled through the Redhawks' post defense and hit a reverse layup off the glass. No one benefited more from the Redhawks' lax perimeter defense than Brock Jacobson, a 3-point specialist who hadn't hit many 3s this season. Jacobson broke out of a season-long slump with nine points -- all from beyond the arc. Center Jiri Hubalek, whose poor play landed him at the end of McDermott's bench, responded strongly against the Redhawks. Hubalek scored nine points during his first shift on the floor after playing five scoreless minutes in Iowa State's loss at No. 3 Ohio State on Tuesday.
